To select all "a" elements except those with a class of "button" using CSS, you can use the ":not" pseudo-class together with the class selector. Here's an example:

```
a:not(.button) {
  /* CSS styles for all "a" elements except those with a class of "button" */
}
```

This will apply any styles you specify only to "a" elements that don't have the class "button".

If you want to target only anchor tags that don't have the "button" class and don't have the "dark" class, you can combine the ":not" and ":not()" selectors. Here is the CSS code that accomplishes this:

```
a:not(.button):not([class*="dark"]) {
  /* Styles to be applied to all anchor tags that don't have "button" and "dark" classes */
}
```

This code uses the CSS attribute selector to apply styles only to "a" elements that don't have classes containing the word "dark". The asterisk (*) selector matches any class name that contains the word "dark", so this will match classes like "theme-dark" or "background-dark".

