I apologize if the previous solution didn't work for you. Here's a revised example that should work using Astro, Preact, and Tailwind:

First, you need to add the following classes to your Tailwind CSS file:

```
.scroll-snap-start {
  scroll-snap-align: start;
}

.scroll-snap-end {
  scroll-snap-align: end;
}

.scroll-snap-mand {
  scroll-snap-type: y mandatory;
}
```

Then, you can add the following code to your Astro/Preact page:

```
<section class="h-screen overflow-y-scroll scroll-snap-mand">
  <div class="h-screen scroll-snap-start">
    <!-- First section content -->
  </div>
  <div class="h-screen">
    <!-- Second section content -->
  </div>
  <div class="h-screen scroll-snap-end">
    <!-- Third section content -->
  </div>
</section>
```

This code sets the height of the "section" element to 100% of the viewport height, adds the "overflow-y-scroll" class to enable vertical scrolling, and sets the "scroll-snap-type" property to "y mandatory" to snap the sections into place as you scroll.

Each section is set to 100% of the viewport height with the "h-screen" class and the "scroll-snap-start" and "scroll-snap-end" classes are added to the first and last sections to indicate the start and end of each section.

This code should work in most modern browsers, but if you're still having issues, you may need to add vendor prefixes or use a JavaScript-based solution for older browsers.

Sure! In the Astro landing page project, the "rotate" animation for the theme switcher button is achieved using CSS transforms and keyframe animations.

First, the button is defined in the "ThemeSwitcher" component in the "components/ThemeSwitcher.js" file. The button is an SVG element with a "path" element for the icon. Here's the relevant code:

```
import { useTheme } from 'astro';
import { Moon, Sun } from 'react-feather';

export default function ThemeSwitcher() {
  const { setTheme, colorMode } = useTheme();

  function toggleTheme() {
    setTheme(colorMode === 'light' ? 'dark' : 'light');
  }

  return (
    <div onClick={toggleTheme} className="cursor-pointer select-none">
      <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
        <path d={colorMode === 'light' ? Sun.path : Moon.path} fill="#FFF" />
      </svg>
    </div>
  );
}
```

In the CSS file, the button is styled with the "theme-switcher" class, which sets the position, size, and other basic styling properties. The "theme-switcher:hover" and "theme-switcher:focus" selectors add a "transform: scale(1.1);" property to the button, which increases its size slightly when hovered or focused.

The "rotate" animation is achieved using keyframe animations and the "animation" property in the "theme-switcher.active" selector. Here's the relevant CSS code:

```
.theme-switcher {
  /* Basic styling properties */
}

.theme-switcher:hover,
.theme-switcher:focus {
  transform: scale(1.1);
}

.theme-switcher.active {
  animation: rotate 1s linear infinite;
}

@keyframes rotate {
  from {
    transform: rotate(0deg);
  }
  to {
    transform: rotate(360deg);
  }
}
```

The "theme-switcher.active" selector adds the "rotate" animation, which rotates the button 360 degrees over a 1-second period. The "linear" keyword specifies that the animation should proceed at a constant rate, and the "infinite" keyword specifies that the animation should repeat indefinitely.

When the "toggleTheme" function is called in the "ThemeSwitcher" component, the "setTheme" function is used to change the color mode of the theme. This causes the "colorMode" variable to be updated, which in turn changes the icon displayed in the "path" element. When the button is clicked, the "theme-switcher.active" class is added to the button briefly, triggering the "rotate" animation.

To create a scroll effect where the viewport scrolls exactly 100vh in one movement and the screen shakes at the end of the scroll, you can use the "scroll-behavior" CSS property to create a smooth scroll effect, and then use JavaScript or a CSS animation to create the shake effect.

Here's an example of how you might implement this technique:

HTML
```
<section class="scroll-section">
  <!-- Section content goes here -->
</section>
```

CSS
```
.scroll-section {
  height: 100vh;
  scroll-snap-align: start; /* Optional: snaps the section to the top of the viewport */
  scroll-behavior: smooth; /* Enables smooth scrolling */
}
```

JavaScript
```
// Find the first scrollable element that matches the ".scroll-section" selector
const section = document.querySelector('.scroll-section');

// Listen for the "wheel" event and prevent the default behavior
section.addEventListener('wheel', event => {
  event.preventDefault();

  // Determine the direction of the scroll
  const direction = event.deltaY > 0 ? 1 : -1;

  // Calculate the distance to the next scroll position (100vh)
  const scrollTop = section.scrollTop;
  const scrollHeight = section.scrollHeight;
  const clientHeight = section.clientHeight;
  const scrollPosition = Math.round((scrollTop + direction * clientHeight) / clientHeight) * clientHeight;
  const distance = scrollPosition - scrollTop;

  // Animate the scrolling with a delay
  section.style.scrollBehavior = 'unset'; // Disable smooth scrolling
  section.style.transform = `translateY(${distance}px)`;
  section.style.transition = `transform 1.5s ease-in-out`;
  setTimeout(() => {
    section.style.transform = 'translateY(0)';
    section.style.transition = 'transform 1s cubic-bezier(.25,.84,.44,1.01)';
  }, 1500);
});
```

This code sets up a "wheel" event listener on the scrollable element, which allows the user to scroll with their mouse or trackpad. When the user scrolls, the event handler calculates the distance to the next "snap" position (which is exactly 100vh), then animates the scrolling
